title: [CALCITE-1828] - Push the FILTER clause into Druid as a Filtered Aggregator
body:
## A few design/implementation decisions:

### There were two ways to add support for factoring out filters from filter clauses (for data pruning and simplification):
1. Add a new `Filter` `RelNode` in between the current `RelNode`s in `DruidQuery`
2. Add a new `RexNode` member in `DruidQuery` that would have acted as a "alternative" filter.

I chose to go with option 1 because `DruidQuery` uses the `RelNode`s quite heavily in it's internal logic, and thus if I were to go with option 2 I would have had to add extra logic in those places to check if there was an "alternative" filter. This would have been messier (and more error prone) than the current approach.

### Instead of adding another Rule, `DruidAggregateProjectRule` was modified
There would have been little difference between a new rule and the old `DruidAggregateProjectRule`, so it made more sense to modify the existing rule. As you can see, most of the changes are just additional checks.

### An always false expression is pushed to Druid in some cases
In the `optimizeFilteredAggregations` method, sometimes the simplified expression will be `false`. Druid is unable to handle a filter that is simply "false", so the unsimplified filter to pushed into Druid, even though it's unsatisfiable. Normally when calcite encounters a always false filter, it doesn't use Druid, however in the optimization phase for filtered aggregations it's too late to go that route.

title: [CALCITE-1803] - Push Project that follows Aggregate down to Druid
body:
Changed files:
calcite-druid/
DruidQuery.java
DruidRules.java
DruidConnectionImpl.java
DruidAdapterIT.java

Allow some relational Project nodes to be pushed into DruidQuery and let the druid query to finish pushed computation.

The implementation now supports following [Post Aggregator in Druid](http://druid.io/docs/0.10.0/querying/post-aggregations.html) (Project after Aggregate in terms of Calcite relational Algebra):

- Arithmetic operation(+,-,*,quotient)
- HyperUniqueCardinality (Change is temporary for now, expecting to change after [CALC-1787](https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CALCITE-1787)) 
- FieldAccessor

Changes on DruidQuery.java:

- Modify the valid signature of `DruidQuery`. Allow post Project to be pushed in. (Using `o` to represent project after aggregate.
- Add a field as a `ImmutableMap` to store the post-aggregation Json representation object in a `DruidQuery`.
- Add `JsonPostAggregation` classes to represent post-aggregate. They are similar to `JsonAggregation`.
- Add a public method `getJsonPostAggregation` to recursively parse Project `RelNode` to a corresponding `JsonPostAggregation` objects.
- Modify the method to compute the signature of Druid Query in order to correctly add character to show post project.
- Modify the method to compute `rowType` of `DruidQuery` correctly after Post Project get pushed in.

Changes on DruidRules.java

- Add a DruidPostAggregationProjectRule to push down projects that can be replaced by post-aggregator in druid.
- scanProject method will parse the Project `RelNode` to `JsonPostAggregation` objects and give correct fieldName of each output column in Project `RelNode`.
- splitProject method has a similar logic to the splitProject method. It will push as much as RexNode to DruidQuery and change the outer Project correspondingly.

Changes on DruidConnectionImpl.java

- Modify the `parseField` method to correctly handle result Json from druid. Right now, quotient Post-aggregator result will give String as result that represents Infinity and Not a Number. ([Test cases](https://git.corp.yahoo.com/zhumayun/calcite/blob/post_aggs_pull_request/druid/src/test/java/org/apache/calcite/test/DruidAdapterIT.java#L2365) to show those condition)

Changes on DruidAdapterIT.java

- Test cases are added to check druid query sent out, plan gave by planner and final results.

title: [CALCITE-1069] In Aggregate, deprecate indicators, and allow GROUPING…
body:
… to be used as an aggregate function

Deprecate the Aggregate.indicator field (strongly encouraging people
to set it to false) and to allow GROUPING (and its synonym, GROUP_ID)
to be used as an aggregate function. It will be handled at implement
time.

With indicator = false, even queries with more than one grouping set
will just output the join keys and the aggregate functions. A join key
will be nullable if it doesn't appear in all grouping sets.

The output row type of Aggregate will be more consistent, and this will
have benefits such as fewer bugs in rules.

Add RelBuilder.rename().

Remove SqlValidatorNamespace.translate() and
SqlQualified.suffixTranslated().

RelMetadataQuery instance is held by planner and carried by the call to the rule. Most places the RMQ was needed in onMatch, where the call is available, or on a method called form onMatch where it could easily be passed as parameter. LoptMultiJoin functions needed RMQ and I had to pass the parameter to several functions.
Since RelNode can get the planner (via cluster) de-facto any reference to a RelNode can retrieve the needed RMQ. I used this in places where the call was not available. This includes also the deprecated functions like getRows.

[CALCITE-1780][core] Add [required Order] and [requiresOver] paramete…
body:
Currently org.apache.calcite.sql.validate.SqlUserDefinedAggFunction calls the constructor of SqlAggFunction:
```

Protected SqlAggFunction (
       String name,
       SqlIdentifier sqlIdentifier,
       SqlKind kind,
       SqlReturnTypeInference returnTypeInference,
       SqlOperandTypeInference operandTypeInference,
       SqlOperandTypeChecker operandTypeChecker,
       SqlFunctionCategory funcType,
       Boolean requiresOrder,
       Boolean requiresOver) 
```
The requiresOrder = false, requiresOver = false. as follow:

```
Public SqlUserDefinedAggFunction (SqlIdentifier opName,
       SqlReturnTypeInference returnTypeInference,
       SqlOperandTypeInference operandTypeInference,
       SqlOperandTypeChecker operandTypeChecker, AggregateFunction function) {
     Super (Util.last (opName.names), opName, SqlKind.OTHER_FUNCTION,
         ReturnTypeInference, operandTypeInference, operandTypeChecker,
         SqlFunctionCategory.USER_DEFINED_FUNCTION, false, false);
     This.function = function;
   } 
```
In this PR. add `required Order` and `requiresOver` parameters to the constructor of `SqlUserDefinedAggregate Function`.

[CALCITE-1742] Create a read-consistent view of CalciteSchema for each statement compilation
body:
New interface: Schema#snapshot(long)
1) One root schema per Connection (as usual), which can evolve over time and return updated contents if the underlying database metadata has changed.
2) Create a snapshot of the root schema when creating prepare context, let it be part of the CalciteSignature and be eventually passed over to DataContext.
This ensures that schema updates will be visible to the subsequent new statements and that schema is read consistent for a specific statement.

Tests:
MultiJdbcSchemaJoinTest#testSchemaCache() is no longer valid, as a new table should always be visible to the next statement after "CREATE TABLE" statement regardless of cache being on or off. Instead, I took advantage of the original test logic and demonstrated that a statement prepared previous to "ALTER TABLE" should still be seeing the old table definition while a new statement that starts over should see the new table definition.
